 their bodies and constructed communities of care to mitigate and make sense of the risks of pregnancy and childbirth. Drawing on medical texts, legal documents, poetry, amulets, funerary art, and more, she shows how these communities were deeply human yet never just human. Freidin demonstrates how patients and caregivers took their place alongside divine and material agencies to guard against the risks inherent to childbearing. She vividly illustrates how these efforts and vital networks offer a new window onto Romans’ anxieties about order, hierarchy, and the individual’s place in the empire and cosmos.Unearthing a risky world that is both familiar and not our own, Birthing Romans reveals how mistakes, misfortunes, and interventions in childbearing were seen to have far-reaching consequences, reverberating across generations and altering the course of people’s lives, their family histories, and even the fate of an empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChildbirthxSocial aspectszRome. 0aChildbirthzRomexHistory. 0aPregnancyxSocial aspectszRome. 0aPregnancyzRomexHistory. 0aReproductive healthxSocial aspectszRome. 0aReproductive healthzRomexHistory. 0aWomenzRomexSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh  aAncient Medicine.  aAncient Rome.  aAncient Science.  aAnna Bonnell Freidin.  aBirthing Romans: Childbearing and Its Risks in Imperial Rome.  aBodies.  aCare.  aChildbearing.  aChildbirth.  aChildhood.  aGender.  aImperialism.  aMagic.  aMidwife.  aMidwifery.  aMotherhood.  aPregnancy.  aProcreation.  aPronatalism.  aReligion.  aReproduction.  aRisk.  aRoman archeology.  aRoman history.  aSoranus.  aUncertainty.  aWomen.  aamulets.  aancient history.  aancient world.  agynecology.  aroman empire.  awomen.08iTitl